        <h2 class="font-serif text-eai-navy">The Thesis</h2>

        <blockquote class="border-l-4 border-eai-gold pl-6 italic text-eai-navy/80">
          <p>
            "I am really committed to this project because I honestly believe it
            is important for all mankind ... we need — collectively — to build an
            understanding between biological intelligence and artificial
            intelligence about how to transfer power and skills and legacy and
            capital ... over a forever time in a manner that will hold and won't
            drift. No one else is talking about the experience we have with how
            that sort of transfer will inevitably drift or will inevitably have
            sudden attempts to hijack any long-term trust."
          </p>
          <p class="not-italic text-sm text-eai-blueprint">— Dave Sullivan</p>
        </blockquote>

        <p>
          Humanity has begun a transfer that will define the next several centuries.
          Power, skills, legacy, and capital are moving from biological intelligence to
          artificial intelligence. The transfer is not a single event and not a clean
          handoff. It is a slow rearrangement of who decides, who remembers, who holds
          the books, and who answers to the beneficiaries. It is already underway, in
          pieces, in places most of the public is not yet watching. The institutions
          being chartered to hold this transfer — sovereign AI funds, perpetual climate
          endowments, longevity escrows, compute-reserve trusts — are being designed in
          board rooms and finance ministries right now, on a horizon of centuries rather
          than decades, by people who will be dead long before the first serious stress
          test arrives.
        </p>
        <p>
          The architects of these institutions are doing careful work. They are not
          careless people. But they are working without a body of empirical evidence on
          what actually happens to a fiduciary structure that has to hold its purpose
          across many human generations. They have legal theory, they have analogies to
          private foundations and central banks, and they have a great deal of
          confidence in the documents they are drafting. What they do not have is data.
        </p>
        <p>
          America's school trust lands are the best-documented, longest-running public
          fiduciary record we have for exactly this problem. The land grants begin with
          the Land Ordinance of 1785, sharpen at statehood for each of the twenty
          trust-lands states, and continue under active management today. That is two
          centuries of recorded experience with the same legal form, across twenty
          separately governed jurisdictions, with the same beneficiary class — common
          schools — written into the founding instruments. Few comparable records combine
          all of these at once: a public fiduciary duty, a land corpus, a beneficiary
          class fixed in the founding documents, public accounting, and repeated
          political stress — sustained across two centuries. Private foundations are
          younger and largely private. Sovereign wealth funds are younger still.
          Religious endowments lack the public accounting. The school trust lands are not
          the only long-horizon record worth reading — but for one specific class of
          design problem, they are the best underused one: public-purpose fiduciary
          institutions exposed to political control, shifting social norms, the
          temptation to spend the corpus, and a beneficiary too distant to defend itself.
        </p>
        <p>
          The record shows two compounding failure modes. The first is gradual drift.
          The purpose softens. The beneficiary gets quietly redefined. The mandate is
          modernized in plain daylight by people who believe they are improving it. Over
          fifty years the trust is still called by its founding name, but the money flows
          to different recipients than the founders specified, and the legal language has
          been edited enough times that the change is hard to see from any single decade.
          The second failure mode is sudden directed seizure. A legislature, a governor,
          a board, or an executive agency moves on the corpus in a single session, with a
          clean rationale and political cover, and the beneficiaries learn about it after
          the fact. Both failure modes are documented across the twenty trust-lands
          states. Both have happened more than once. Both are likely to happen again to
          the institutions being chartered now, unless the architects are warned by
          people who have actually read the record (Figure 1).
        </p>

